Recently, cyber attacks on the business world have become more frequent.
Access to data from companies such as JP Morgan, Yahoo, Home Depot, and Target has caused them losses of hundreds of millions, and in some cases even billions of dollars.
It doesn't take too many such attacks to damage the global economy.
The public sector is also not immune to such problems.
From 2012 to 2014, there was a significant data leak in the US Office of Personnel Management.
Access to the security and fingerprint verification data of 22 million employees was compromised.
There are known attempts by hackers sponsored by government agencies to influence the results of elections in a number of countries with the help of stolen data.
The two most recent disclosures involve the Bundestag, the German Federal Parliament, and the theft of emails from the US Democratic National Committee.
The cyber threat affects our democratic processes.
The situation is even getting worse.
As computer technology evolves, data protection systems become increasingly vulnerable.
A new type of computer technology is also of concern — computing on quantum computers, which use the microscopic properties of nature to enormously increase computing power.
It is so powerful that it can crack many modern encryption systems.
Is the situation so hopeless?
Maybe it's time to pack up our vital data and prepare for the coming digital apocalypse.
I would say, " Not yet."
Quantum computers are still in development, and it will take many years before they are put into practice.
More important is the fact that there are major breakthroughs in the field of encryption.
For me, this is a particularly exciting time in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, when I learned about the new possibility of creating quantum effects that do not exist in nature, I was very excited.
I was intrigued by the idea of applying the fundamental laws of physics to create more secure encryption.
Today, a number of companies and laboratories around the world, including mine, are working on these technologies to put them into practice.
Right.
Now we are preparing to fight the quantum with the help of the quantum.
So how does it all work?
First, let's take a quick look at the world of encryption.
To do this, we will need a briefcase, some important documents that we want to send to our friend, James Bond, and a lock to keep everything safe.
Since our information is top secret, we need a special briefcase.
It has a special combination lock: when it is closed, it converts all the text in the documents to random numbers.
You put the documents in the briefcase, close the lock — at this very moment all the documents are converted to random numbers — and send the briefcase to James.
While the briefcase is on its way, you call James to tell him the code.
After receiving the briefcase, he enters the code, the documents are decrypted, and voila — you just sent an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) A funny example, but it illustrates three important coding elements.
The code — we call it the "encryption key".
It's like a password.
Call James to tell him the combination code of the lock.
This is called " key exchange» —
guarantee that you will safely get the encryption key from the right place.
And a lock that encodes and decodes the document.
This is called the "encoding algorithm".
Using the key, it converts the text in the documents to random numbers.
A good algorithm will encode in such a way that without a key, the document is very difficult to decipher.
The importance of encryption is that if someone gets hold of a briefcase and breaks it without using the encryption key and the encoding algorithm, they still won't be able to read its contents.
The information will look like a set of random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure way to exchange keys to transfer the encryption key to the desired location.
However, the rapid development of computing power threatens a number of modern methods of key exchange.
Consider one of the most widely used systems today — RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it was estimated that it would take 40 quadrillion years to crack a 426-bit RSA key.
In 1994, just 17 years later, the code was cracked.
As computers became more powerful, we had to use more complex codes.
Today we usually use 2,048 or 4,096 bits.
As you can see, the creators of the code and the hackers are engaged in an ongoing battle, trying to outsmart each other.
And when quantum computers appear in the next 10-15 years, they will be able to crack the complex mathematics that underlies many modern encryption systems even faster.
A quantum computer is likely to turn our current secure fortress into a simple house of cards.
We must find a way to defend our fortress.
In recent years, there has been an increasing amount of research into the use of quantum effects to enhance cryptographic protection.
Some interesting discoveries have been made.
Remember the three main elements of encryption: high-quality keys, secure key exchange, and a complex algorithm?
Advances in science and technology threaten two of these three elements.
First, the keys themselves.
Random numbers are the fundamental building blocks of encryption keys.
But to date, they are not entirely random.
Today, we create encryption keys from sequences of random numbers generated from software, so-called pseudo-random numbers.
In the numbers generated by a program or a mathematical formula, one way or another, there is a certain pattern.
The less random numbers are — in scientific terms, the less entropy they contain — the easier it is to predict them.
Recently, several casinos have been the victims of an ingenious attack.
Combinations at the output of slot machines were recorded for some time, after which they were analyzed.
This allowed cybercriminals to redesign the pseudo-random number generator that controls the reels.
This, in turn, made it possible to predict the spin of the reels with high accuracy and get a big win.
Encryption keys can also be exposed to similar risks.
Secure encryption requires a truly random number generator.
For many years, scientists have been looking for the possibility of creating such a generator.
But most attempts today are either not random enough, not fast enough, or difficult to repeat.
But the quantum world is based on randomness.
Therefore, it makes sense to take advantage of this fact.
Devices that can measure quantum effects can also create an infinite stream of random numbers at high speed,
which will prevent all these potential criminals from entering the casino.
A number of top universities and companies around the world are engaged in creating truly random number generators.
The first quantum generator created in my company was one meter by two meters and placed on an optical table.
Later, we were able to reduce it to the size of a server box.
Today, it's the size of a PCI card plugged into a standard computer.
This is the world's fastest truly random number generator.
Its performance is a billion random numbers per second.
Today, it is used to strengthen the security system by cloud providers, banks, and government agencies around the world.
(Applause) But even with such a generator, the second big problem remains unsolved: the threat to secure key exchange.
Modern methods of key exchange are not compatible with a quantum computer.
The quantum solution to this problem is called "quantum key distribution" or QKD, which is based on a fundamental, paradoxical characteristic of quantum mechanics.
A quantum particle changes depending on its observation.
Here is an example of how it works.
Let's go back to exchanging the codes for the lock with James Bond.
Only this time, instead of calling James with the code message, we'll use quantum effects on the laser to create the code and send it to James over a conventional optical fiber.
We believe that Dr. Know will try to hack access to the data exchange.
Fortunately, his attempts to catch the quantum keys in transit will leave fingerprints that James and you will be able to detect.
This will eliminate the intercepted keys.
And the remaining keys can be used for enhanced data protection.
Since such security is based on the fundamental laws of physics, a quantum computer or even any supercomputer of the future will not be able to crack it.
My team and I are working with leading universities, as well as the defense sector, to develop this promising technology into next-generation security tools.
The Internet of Things heralds an era when 25-30 billion devices will interact, which is projected to appear by 2020.
For our society to function properly in the world of the Internet of Things, trust in the systems that support these devices is vital.
I bet that quantum technology can provide that trust, allowing us to take full advantage of the amazing innovations that will enrich our lives.
Thanks.
