When the iceberg melts, I breathe in its ancient atmosphere.
When an iceberg melts, it releases fresh, mineral-rich water that feeds many forms of life.
I approach photographing these icebergs as creating portraits of my ancestors, knowing that in these individual moments they exist in this image, and that it will never happen again.
They do not die when they melt; this is not the end, but the continuation of their path in the cycle of life.
Sometimes the ice in the icebergs I photograph is very young — it's only a couple of thousand years old.
