Today I would like to show you how we will do different things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will be self-assembling, reproducing and repairing themselves.
So, I'm going to show you what I think is the current stage of industrial development, and then compare it to some natural systems.
So, at the current stage of industrial development, we have skyscrapers-2.5 years, from 500,000 to a million parts, quite complex, new amazing technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have amazing machines that can take us to space-5 years, 2.5 million parts.
But on the other hand, if we look at natural systems, we see proteins of two million species that can assemble in 10,000 nanoseconds, or a DNA chain with three billion base pairs that we can copy in about an hour.
So natural systems, for all their complexity, are extremely efficient, far more efficient than anything we can build, far more complex than anything we can build.
They are much more efficient in terms of energy.
They are almost never wrong.
And they can regenerate themselves over a long lifetime.
So, there is something very interesting about natural systems.
And if we can bring that into our man-made environment, our way of creating things will have tremendous potential.
And I think the key is self - assembly.
So, if we want to use self-assembly in our physical environment, I think we need to consider four key factors.
First, we need to decipher the complexity of what we want to build - our buildings and machines.
And you need to decompose them into a simple sequence - the basic DNA of the construction processes.
Then we will need programmable parts that can understand this sequence and use it to collapse or reassemble.
We will need some amount of energy that will allow us to activate all this, make the parts able to assemble according to the program.
And we need some kind of fallback bug-fixing system to ensure that what we want is built successfully.
I'm going to show you some of the projects that my colleagues at EmAiTi and I are working on to achieve this self-assembling future.
The first two are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These projects are large-scale reconfigurable robots-2.5 and 3.5 meter squirrels.
They have built-in mechanical electrical devices, sensors.
You write out what you want to curl up into, a sequence of angles-minus 120, minus 120, 0, 0, 120, minus 120 - something like that; a sequence of angles or turns, and you send that sequence down the cord.
Each block receives its own message-minus 120. He turns at this angle, checks if everything is correct, and passes the information to the neighbor.
And these are the brilliant scientists, engineers, and designers who worked on this project.
And I think it really brings out the question: is there a different scale possible here?
I mean, thousands of dollars, a lot of man-hours to make this 2.5-meter robot.
Can we actually zoom in? Can we really build robotics into every part?
The next project solves this question, considers the passive character, or tries to obtain modifiability passively.
But it goes a step further and tries to get a real calculation.
At its core, it has the most fundamental building block of computing, the logic element of a digital integrated circuit directly in each part.
This is the "And-NOT" element.
You have one tetrahedron element that will do all the calculations, and two tetrahedrons to input.
One is for user input, this is how you lay the bricks.
The other is for information from the previous laid brick.
And then it outputs the information in three-dimensional space.
So, this means that the user can start running moving the bricks in the desired direction.
His calculations are based on what was done earlier and what you told him to do.
And now it begins to move in three-dimensional space-up or down.
On the left side, [1,1] input is 0 on the output, moving down.
On the right side, [0,0] input is 1 on the output, which means moving up.
And what's really important, our structures now contain blueprints for what we want to build.
They contain all the information about what was built.
So, this means that we have some form of self-reproduction.
In this case, I call it self-directed reproduction, because the structures contain clear drawings.
If errors appear, you can replace the part.
All local information is saved so that you know how to fix it.
So you can have something that moves and reads the information and can transfer it from one part to another.
It is built directly inside, without external control.
The latest project I'm going to show you is called Biased Circuits, and it's probably the most exciting example of what we have right now of passive self-assembling systems.
It combines the ability to reconfigure and program and creates a completely passive system.
At the core, we have a chain of elements.
All elements are completely identical, and are offset.
So every chain or every element wants to turn right or left.
And when you assemble a circuit, you are essentially programming it.
You tell each block where it should turn: to the right or to the left.
So when you shake the chain, it collapses into the configuration you have programmed - in this case, a spiral, or in this case, two cubes next to each other.
So in general, you can program any three-dimensional shape - or one-dimensional, two-dimensional-from these completely passive circuits.
So, what does this tell us about the future?
I think it tells us that there are new possibilities for self-assembly, replication, repair in our physical structures, buildings, machines.
New programming is possible in these parts.
And from here, you have new possibilities in computing.
We will have spatial computers.
Imagine that our buildings, our bridges, our cars, all our bricks could do calculations.
This is an amazing parallel and distributed computing power, new design possibilities.
This is an incredible potential.
I think that the projects I have shown you are only a small step towards the future, if we implement these new technologies, towards a new self-assembling future.
Thanks.
