The fire in the Cathedral of Saints Peter and Paul occurred on July 18.
More than 200 firefighters fought for several hours for the monument of Gothic architecture.
However, they were unable to save the stained glass windows of the time of Louis XII and the unique organ of the Baroque era.
The situation was brought under control only three hours after the fire started.
As a result of the incident, no one was injured.
The current fire is not the first in the history of the temple.
In 1972, a fire destroyed its roof.
It took 13 years to eliminate the consequences of that fire.
For parishioners, the cathedral was reopened only in 1985.
