It is believed that only sighted people can drive a car.
Until recently, it was believed that for a blind person, safe and independent driving is an impossible task.
Hello, I'm Denis Hong, and we give the blind freedom and independence by designing cars for the visually impaired.
Before I talk about this car for the blind, I'll briefly talk about another project I've been working on, called the DARPA Urban Challenge.
The project was to create a self-driving robot car.
The driver presses "start", and without his participation, the car reaches its destination.
In 2007, our team won half a million dollars, taking third place in this competition.
Around the same time, the National Federation of the Blind, or NSF, set a research committee the task of developing a car that could be driven independently and safely by a blind person.
We decided to try our hand at it because we thought, " Hey, what's so hard about that?
We already have an autonomous car.
We put a blind man in it , and that's the end of it, isn't it?»
(Laughter) But we were deeply mistaken.
The NSF wanted to get not just a car that would transport the blind, but a car that the blind could drive independently.
So we had to reject everything and start from scratch.
So, to test this crazy idea, we developed a small prototype buggy car to test the feasibility of the project.
And in the summer of 2009, we invited blind young people from all over the country and gave them the opportunity to experience this car.
It was an amazing experience.
But the catch is that this car was designed to be driven in a strictly controlled environment, namely in a flat, enclosed parking lot, where even the traffic lanes are limited by red signal cones.
Due to this success, we decided to take the next big step and develop a real car that could be driven on real roads.
So, how does it work?
Well, it's quite a complex system, but let me clarify, maybe even simplify it.
So, it includes three components.
These are tactile perception, computation, and non-visual interfaces.
Since the driver can't see anything, the system must perceive the environment and collect information for the driver.
For this purpose, the initial parameter meter is used.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration, like a person's inner ear.
This information is then transmitted to the GPS device to estimate the vehicle's location.
Two cameras are used to detect traffic lanes on the road
and three laser rangefinders.
Lasers scan the space around the car to detect various objects: an approaching oncoming or overtaking car, any obstacles encountered on the road or around the car.
Then all this huge amount of information is fed into the computer, and the computer performs two steps.
First of all, it is processing this information to get an idea of the space: determining traffic lanes on the road, identifying obstacles, and then communicating this information to the driver.
The system is also smart enough to calculate the safest way to drive a car.
So, we can also give recommendations on how to operate the car.
But the problem is how to convey this information and instructions to a blind person who does not have the quick and accurate reaction necessary for driving?
For this purpose, we have developed a number of interface technologies for the blind:
A three-dimensional ping sound system, a vibrating vest, a steering wheel with beeps, a special prosthetic leg, and even shoes that put pressure on the foot.
But today we will only talk about three types of these special interfaces.
The first interface is called DriveGrip.
This is a pair of gloves with motors on the knuckles of the fingers, instructing the driver how to steer: the direction and angle of rotation.
The other device is SpeedStrip.
Initially, this is a massage chair.
It was disassembled and the vibrating elements were rearranged in it. Vibration is used to transmit speed information to the driver, as well as to guide the use of the gas and brake pedals.
So, here you can see how the computer perceives the space around the car. And since the vibration cannot be seen, red LEDs are installed on the driver to demonstrate the process.
This is sensory data, which is transmitted to the devices via a computer.
The DriveGrip and SpeedStrip devices are very efficient.
But the problem is that these are educational prompting devices.
They don't actually give you the freedom to manage, do they?
The on-board computer gives the driver commands: "left", "right", "speed up", "stop".
We call him the " annoying backseat passenger."
Therefore, we are moving away from educational prompting devices and focusing on informing devices.
An excellent example of such an interface is AirPix.
This is a kind of monitor for the blind.
A small panel with many holes through which compressed air escapes, thereby creating images.
A blind person can put their palm up to this panel and "see" the traffic lanes on the roadway and obstacles.
Also, the driver can change the frequency with which the air exits and, possibly, the air temperature.
That is, it is an interface for displaying multidimensional data.
So, here you can see the left and right camera of the car, and how the computer processes and sends this information to the AirPix panel.
Here we demonstrate a simulator, a blind person driving a car using AirPix.
This simulator turned out to be very useful for training blind drivers, as well as for quickly testing ideas for using different types of special interfaces.
This is how the system works in short.
After all, this is a prototype car for the blind. And they won't let him out on the roadway until they're sure he's absolutely safe.
And I sincerely believe that this is quite likely.
And yet, will society accept such a radical idea?
How much will the rules of car insurance change?
Under what conditions will a driver's license be issued?
Beyond the technological challenges, there are so many pitfalls that need to be overcome before this becomes a reality.
Of course, the main goal of this project is to develop a car for the blind.
However, it is possible that the side technologies developed during this project will prove to be an invaluable contribution to our lives.
Our sensors work regardless of the time of day, fog, or rain.
We can use these technologies together with new special interfaces to improve the safety of cars for the sighted.
Or for the blind. Find their use in everyday household appliances, in educational institutions, in offices.
Just imagine: the teacher in the classroom writes on the blackboard, and the blind student can see and read what is written using these special interfaces.
It's priceless.
So what I have shown you today is just the beginning.
Thank you very much.
(Applause)
